#X text 48 112 This is the same score and example as before \, but we're now sending information to a [metronome] object \, which understands the 'timesig' message and can also get tempo information to give us a "click track"., f 45;
#X text 112 19 The time signature does not need to match the given sequence of note durations \, which means you can make mistakes and it will not correct it. If you screw up and it doesn't match \, what actually counts is the sum of durations. The actual time signature is then rather meaningless and you can just ignore it. It is useful though for reading purposes \, and you could use the data output to feed a [metronome] object \, which actually understands it \, for click tracking., f 98;
